Iâ€™ll never forget waking up to the news. I dressed my one-year old daughter and I couldnâ€™t get to College Station fast enough.
To this day itâ€™s hard to comprehend that what I was witnessing in front of me was reality.
We attended the game vs texas and there wasnâ€™t a dry eye at Kyle Field that day. I held my daughter tightly in my arms throughout the game all the while knowing there were Aggie Parents whose babies were never coming home. As I stood in the stands my heart was heavy for those students::: their parents and loved ones::: and our entire Aggie Family. I remember them today and all
of the courageous people who rushed in to help.
My daughter who was in my arms as I watched the bonfire recovery effort and stood through the game is now Class of 2020 and my youngest is Class of 2025.
I will remember our twelve always. Their spirit lives on.

I was at Bonfire the night it fell.

My two dogs had been missing for days::: a neighbor suggested I look there. My sister and I watched these able-bodied boys pull out the next log for the stack::: backlit by lights that would haunt me for decades.

I was less than a month away from becoming a certified EMT. I had been up late every night that week::: and I went home because I was tired. It took a really::: really long time to accept the fact that God did not want me to stay there those extra 20 minutesâ€¦

God bless these kids and their families. They were way better Aggies than I ever was::: and their loss doesnâ€™t get any easier.

Dear Dr. Banks:

Right now::: 19 dogs from Texas A&M Universityâ€™s canine muscular dystrophy (MD) laboratoryâ€”12 of whom are perfectly healthy and adoptableâ€”conti
nue to be warehoused on your campus::: despite the retirement of the lead experimenter and the fact that the lab appears to have little funding for experiments.

The golden retrievers and other dogs from this laboratory are deprived of the very things that would make their lives worth living::: as they spend every day stuck in barren metal cells. The dogs suffering from canine MD have undergone painful and terrifying testing::: and their health has steadily deteriorated to the point where itâ€™s difficult for them even to swallow their own saliva. Video footage shows that the healthy ones pace frantically and bite at the bars of their cages in frustration.

Itâ€™s commendable that Texas A&M made the compassionate decision to stop breeding dogs to develop MD in 2019. Please do the next right thing and use your authority as president to order the release of the surviving dogs so that they may spend their remaining years in warm::: loving adoptive homes.

Thank you for your consideration of this important matter.

Dear Dr. Banks:

Right now::: 19 dogs from Texas A&M Universityâ€™s canine muscular dystrophy (MD) laboratoryâ€”12 of whom are perfectly healthy and adoptableâ€”conti
nue to be warehoused on your campus::: despite the retirement of the lead experimenter and the fact that the lab appears to have little funding for experiments.

The golden retrievers and other dogs from this laboratory are deprived of the very things that would make their lives worth living::: as they spend every day stuck in barren metal cells. The dogs suffering from canine MD have undergone painful and terrifying testing::: and their health has steadily deteriorated to the point where itâ€™s difficult for them even to swallow their own saliva. Video footage shows that the healthy ones pace frantically and bite at the bars of their cages in frustration.

Itâ€™s commendable that Texas A&M made the compassionate decision to stop breeding dogs to develop MD in 2019. Please do the next right thing and use your authority as president to order the release of the surviving dogs so that they may spend their remaining years in warm::: loving adoptive homes.

Thank you for your consideration of this important matter.

Five years ago today::: a light-blond golden retriever was born in Texas A&M Universityâ€™s canine muscular dystrophy laboratory.
Workers named her Elviraâ€”and the nightmare that sheâ€™s endured for the last five years is as depraved as any horror movie.
Experimenters bred her to develop a canine form of muscular dystrophy. Not content to release her after she failed to show symptoms of the debilitating disease::: they instead treated her as nothing more than a breeding machine::: forcing her to give birth to litter after litter of puppiesâ€”each one condemned to suffer in crude experiments as their muscles slowly wasted away. Then experimenters transferred Elvira to the veterinary school to be used in teaching labs.Elvira has never known a real home and the love of a family that every dog deservesâ€”and today::: sheâ€™s spending her fifth birthday locked in a laboratory cage.

We're happy to hear Lady::: Baylor University's mascot::: is once again healthy and thriving!

We know this is a video from Baylor::: but please bear with us... it's worth it to see how Aggie veterinarians from Texas A&M College of Veterinary Medicine & Biomedical Sciences pioneered treatments and worked with her caregivers to get her back to full health.

Baylor University
October 11 at 7:00 PM Â·

"No bear in the world has done what Lady has done."

Over the last two years::: Lady -- one of Baylor's two live bears -- has been on a roller coaster medical journey::: fighting off two different cancer scares and undergoing a pair of first-of-their-kind surgeries. Today::: thanks to incredible work by a team of caregivers::: Lady is once again healthy -- our miracle bear.

See her story for yourself -- in "Lady: The Miracle Bear":

Dear Dr. Banks:

Right now::: 19 dogs from Texas A&M Universityâ€™s canine muscular dystrophy (MD) laboratoryâ€”12 of whom are perfectly healthy and adoptableâ€”conti
nue to be warehoused on your campus::: despite the retirement of the lead experimenter and the fact that the lab appears to have little funding for experiments.

The golden retrievers and other dogs from this laboratory are deprived of the very things that would make their lives worth living::: as they spend every day stuck in barren metal cells. The dogs suffering from canine MD have undergone painful and terrifying testing::: and their health has steadily deteriorated to the point where itâ€™s difficult for them even to swallow their own saliva. Video footage shows that the healthy ones pace frantically and bite at the bars of their cages in frustration.

Itâ€™s commendable that Texas A&M made the compassionate decision to stop breeding dogs to develop MD in 2019. Please do the next right thing and use your authority as president to order the release of the surviving dogs so that they may spend their remaining years in warm::: loving adoptive homes.

Thank you for your consideration of this important matter.

column36: As you know::: in 2019 Texas A&M have ended its horrific MD lab dog-breeding program::: which is a victory for the helpless::: voiceless::: severely harmed dogs whose lives were nothing but misery. Forty years of experiments on dogs for the Muscular Dystrophy experiments failed to produce a cure or even a treatment to reverse MD symptoms in humans. However::: Peter Nghiem::: the laboratoryâ€™s lead experimenter::: has publicly claimed that healthy dogs are adopted out after heâ€™s finished using them. This is a falsehood. Cannoli::: for instance::: had initially been put up for adoption but was instead transferred to the second lab. Three other dogs remain in barren metal cages in Nghiemâ€˜s lab. Nine others were transferred to another Texas A&M laboratory. Others died::: living a horrific life and never knowing the love and comfort of a home. I implore you to close the laboratory::: release all dogs from this lab for adoption into good homes::: and redirect resources toward humane research methods. Right now::: 19 dogs from Texas A&M Universityâ€™s canine muscular dystrophy (MD) laboratoryâ€”12 of whom are perfectly healthy and adoptableâ€”conti
nue to be warehoused on your campus::: despite the retirement of the lead experimenter and the fact that the lab appears to have little funding for experiments.

The golden retrievers and other dogs from this laboratory are deprived of the very things that would make their lives worth living::: as they spend every day stuck in barren metal cells. The dogs suffering from canine MD have undergone painful and terrifying testing::: and their health has steadily deteriorated to the point where itâ€™s difficult for them even to swallow their own saliva. Video footage shows that the healthy ones pace frantically and bite at the bars of their cages in frustration.

Itâ€™s commendable that Texas A&M made the compassionate decision to stop breeding dogs to develop MD in 2019. Please do the next right thing and use your authority as president to order the release of the surviving dogs so that they may spend their remaining years in warm::: loving adoptive homes.

Thank you for your consideration of this important matter.

column66:
At Texas A&M University::: experimenters bred golden retrievers to develop canine muscular dystrophy (MD). This disease ravages their bodies::: causing progressive muscle wasting and weakness.

Video footage shows that the appallingly thin dogs in the laboratory were caged::: sometimes alone::: in barren metal cells and struggled to swallow thin gruelâ€”the only food that they could eat::: given how easily they could choke. Long ropes of saliva hung from the mouths of those whose jaw muscles had weakened. Even balancing was difficult. Dogs with this condition are also at great risk of contracting pneumonia because they can easily inhale liquid. To gauge just how much a dogâ€™s muscles have deteriorated::: experimenters invented a crude technique that could pass for medieval torture: They repeatedly stretch them with a motorized lever in order to cause muscle tears.

Dogs who didnâ€™t have the disease but carried the MD gene were used for breeding. Deprived of loving homes::: they frantically paced across the slatted floors and bit the bars of the small cages in frustration. They didnâ€™t even have the comfort of a blanket.

Forty years of experiments on dogs have failed to produce a cure or even a treatment to reverse MD symptoms in humans. Following an intensive PETA campaign::: in 2019 Texas A&M bowed to pressure and permanently ended its MD laboratory dog-breeding program. The lab appears to have little funding for experiments::: and a number of dogs have been released for adoption. Sadly::: others have died without ever knowing the love and comfort of a home. (Read more here.)

Peter Nghiem::: the laboratoryâ€™s lead experimenter::: has publicly claimed that healthy dogs are adopted out after heâ€™s finished using them. This is a lie. Three such dogs remain in barren metal cages in Nghiemâ€˜s lab. Nine others were transferred to another Texas A&M laboratory::: including Cannoli::: who had initially been put up for adoption. But he was betrayed by the school when he was transferred to the second lab.

Itâ€™s apparent that::: rather than admitting defeat::: the school prefers to warehouse 19 dogs::: even though PETA has offered to take all of them. Close the laboratory::: release all dogs from this lab for adoption into good homes::: and redirect resources toward humane research methods.

Dear Dr. Banks:

Right now::: 19 dogs from Texas A&M Universityâ€™s canine muscular dystrophy (MD) laboratoryâ€”12 of whom are perfectly healthy and adoptableâ€”conti
nue to be warehoused on your campus::: despite the retirement of the lead experimenter and the fact that the lab appears to have little funding for experiments.

The golden retrievers and other dogs from this laboratory are deprived of the very things that would make their lives worth living::: as they spend every day stuck in barren metal cells. The dogs suffering from canine MD have undergone painful and terrifying testing::: and their health has steadily deteriorated to the point where itâ€™s difficult for them even to swallow their own saliva. Video footage shows that the healthy ones pace frantically and bite at the bars of their cages in frustration.

Itâ€™s commendable that Texas A&M made the compassionate decision to stop breeding dogs to develop MD in 2019. Please do the next right thing and use your authority as president to order the release of the surviving dogs so that they may spend their remaining years in warm::: loving adoptive homes.

Thank you for your consideration of this important matter.

just as we shall not be able to take anything out of it.
If we have food and clothing::: we shall be content with that.
Those who want to be rich are falling into temptation and into a trap
and into many foolish and harmful desires:::
which plunge them into ruin and destruction.
For the love of money is the root of all evils:::
and some people in their desire for it have strayed from the faith
and have pierced themselves with many pains.

But you::: man of God::: avoid all this.
Instead::: pursue righteousness::: devotion:::
faith::: love::: patience::: and gentleness.
Compete well for the faith.
Lay hold of eternal life:::
to which you were called when you made the noble confession
in the presence of many witnesses.

Following the September 11th terrorist attacks::: 72 members of Texas A&M Task Force 1 deployed from Aggieland to help assist first responders in New York City.

Since 2001::: they have used their experiences at ground zero to help train first responders from around the world here at Texas A&M.

KAMU Public Broadcasting
September 11 at 11:22 AM Â·

Three original members of Texas A&M Task Force 1 reflect on their deployment to ground zero following the September 11::: 2001::: terrorist attacks in New York City.

The elite urban search and rescue team â€” which had been responding to disasters in Texas for four years at the time â€” took 72 of its members who worked amid the devastation over nine days. It was their first federal assignment since being added to FEMA's team several months earlier.

Today::: the team uses their experiences reacting to disasters to train first responders from around the world here at Texas A&M University.

Video footage shows that the appallingly thin dogs in the laboratory were caged::: sometimes alone::: in barren metal cells and struggled to swallow thin gruelâ€”the only food that they could eat::: given how easily they could choke. Long ropes of saliva hung from the mouths of those whose jaw muscles had weakened. Even balancing was difficult. Dogs with this condition are also at great risk of contracting pneumonia because they can easily inhale liquid. To gauge just how much a dogâ€™s muscles have deteriorated::: experimenters invented a crude technique that could pass for medieval torture: They repeatedly stretch them with a motorized lever in order to cause muscle tears.

Dogs who didnâ€™t have the disease but carried the MD gene were used for breeding. Deprived of loving homes::: they frantically paced across the slatted floors and bit the bars of the small cages in frustration. They didnâ€™t even have the comfort of a blanket.

Dogs affected with canine DM have been subjected to painful and terrifying tests and their health has continually weakened::: to the point where it is difficult for them to even swallow their own saliva. Video footage shows healthy dogs frantically pacing back and forth and chewing on cage bars out of frustration.

It is commendable that in 2019 Texas A&M made the compassionate decision to stop breeding dogs to develop DM. Please continue to do the right thing and use your authority as president to order the release of the surviving dogs so that they can be adopted and live their remaining years in welcoming and loving homes.

At this time::: 19 dogs from the canine muscular dystrophy (DM) laboratory at Texas A&M University (with at least 12 perfectly healthy and adoptable) remain on its campus::: despite the retirement of the lead experimenter and the fact that the laboratory seems to have little funding for the experiments.

In this laboratory::: golden retrievers and other dogs are deprived of everything that gives meaning to their lives::: as they are trapped in desolate metal cells every day. Dogs affected with canine DM have been subjected to painful and terrifying tests and their health has continually weakened::: to the point where it is difficult for them to even swallow their own saliva. Video footage shows healthy dogs frantically pacing back and forth and chewing on cage bars out of frustration.

It is commendable that in 2019 Texas A&M made the compassionate decision to stop breeding dogs to develop DM. Please continue to do the right thing and use your authority as president to order the release of the surviving dogs so that they can be adopted and live their remaining years in welcoming and loving homes.

Dear Dr. Banks:

Right now::: 19 dogs from Texas A&M Universityâ€™s canine muscular dystrophy (MD) laboratoryâ€”12 of whom are perfectly healthy and adoptableâ€”conti

The dogs suffering from canine MD have undergone painful and terrifying testing::: and their health has steadily deteriorated to the point where itâ€™s difficult for them even to swallow their own saliva. Thank you for your consideration of this important matter.

Texas A&M announces plans for full-capacity::: in-person classes for the fall semester: tx.ag/UpdateAug521

Considering the continued infection rates::: Texas A&M asks the campus community to do its part by taking important steps to keep Aggieland healthy and safe.

While Texas A&M does not require vaccinations or wearing of masks::: students::: faculty::: & staff are strongly encouraged to get vaccinated::: wear a mask in public indoor settings::: and frequently wash hands.

As we return to campus for the fall::: students::: faculty::: and staff are required to:
- Read and agree to adhere to university guidelines.
- Participate in the mandatory testing program.
- Complete the Texas A&M COVID-19 report form if one tests positive::: shows symptoms::: or has close contact with someone who received a positive test.
- Quarantine if one tests positive or has been identified as a close contact.

Students who have proof of vaccination will be entered into a drawing for one year of undergraduate or graduate tuition and fees. Faculty and staff who have proof of vaccination will also be entered into random drawings for prizes. Complete rules for these drawings will be made available soon.

column42:
At Texas A&M University::: experimenters bred golden retrievers to develop canine muscular dystrophy (MD). This disease ravages their bodies::: causing progressive muscle wasting and weakness. To gauge just how much a dogâ€™s muscles have deteriorated::: experimenters invented a crude technique that could pass for medieval torture: They repeatedly stretch them with a motorized lever in order to cause muscle tears.
Dogs who didnâ€™t have the disease but carried the MD gene were used for breeding. Deprived of loving homes::: they frantically paced across the slatted floors and bit the bars of the small cages in frustration. They didnâ€™t even have the comfort of a blanket.
Forty years of experiments on dogs have failed to produce a cure or even a treatment to reverse MD symptoms in humans.
Following an intensive PETA campaign::: in 2019 Texas A&M bowed to pressure and permanently ended its MD laboratory dog-breeding program. The lab appears to have little funding for experiments::: and a number of dogs have been released for adoption. Sadly::: others have died without ever knowing the love and comfort of a home.

Peter Nghiem::: the laboratoryâ€™s lead experimenter::: has publicly claimed that healthy dogs are adopted out after heâ€™s finished using them. This is a lie. Three such dogs remain in barren metal cages in Nghiemâ€˜s lab. Nine others were transferred to another Texas A&M laboratory::: including Cannoli::: who had initially been put up for adoption. But he was betrayed by the school when he was transferred to the second lab.
Itâ€™s apparent that::: rather than admitting defeat::: the school prefers to warehouse 19 dogs::: even though PETA has offered to take all of them.

Say Howdy with a deep apology to the dogs Texas A&M tortures. Appalling::: cruel::: inhumane and useless science. This is not "higher education". To gauge just how much a dogâ€™s muscles have deteriorated::: experimenters invented a crude technique that could pass for medieval torture: They repeatedly stretch them with a motorized lever in order to cause muscle tears.

Dogs who didnâ€™t have the disease but carried the MD gene were used for breeding. Deprived of loving homes::: they frantically paced across the slatted floors and bit the bars of the small cages in frustration. They didnâ€™t even have the comfort of a blanket.

Forty years of experiments on dogs have failed to produce a cure or even a treatment to reverse MD symptoms in humans.

Following an intensive PETA campaign::: in 2019 Texas A&M bowed to pressure and permanently ended its MD laboratory dog-breeding program. The lab appears to have little funding for experiments::: and a number of dogs have been released for adoption. Sadly::: others have died without ever knowing the love and comfort of a home. (Read more here.)

Peter Nghiem::: the laboratoryâ€™s lead experimenter::: has publicly claimed that healthy dogs are adopted out after heâ€™s finished using them. This is a lie. Three such dogs remain in barren metal cages in Nghiemâ€˜s lab. Nine others were transferred to another Texas A&M laboratory::: including Cannoli::: who had initially been put up for adoption. But he was betrayed by the school when he was transferred to the second lab.

Itâ€™s apparent that::: rather than admitting defeat::: the school prefers to warehouse 19 dogs::: even though PETA has offered to take all of them.

column32:
At Texas A&M University::: experimenters bred golden retrievers to develop canine muscular dystrophy (MD). This disease ravages their bodies::: causing progressive muscle wasting and weakness.
Video footage shows that the appallingly thin dogs in the laboratory were caged::: sometimes alone::: in barren metal cells and struggled to swallow thin gruelâ€”the only food that they could eat::: given how easily they could choke. Long ropes of saliva hung from the mouths of those whose jaw muscles had weakened. Even balancing was difficult. Dogs with this condition are also at great risk of contracting pneumonia because they can easily inhale liquid. To gauge just how much a dogâ€™s muscles have deteriorated::: experimenters invented a crude technique that could pass for medieval torture: They repeatedly stretch them with a motorized lever in order to cause muscle tears.
Dogs who didnâ€™t have the disease but carried the MD gene were used for breeding. Deprived of loving homes::: they frantically paced across the slatted floors and bit the bars of the small cages in frustration. They didnâ€™t even have the comfort of a blanket.
Forty years of experiments on dogs have failed to produce a cure or even a treatment to reverse MD symptoms in humans.

At Texas A&M University::: experimenters bred golden retrievers to develop canine muscular dystrophy (MD). This disease ravages their bodies::: causing progressive muscle wasting and weakness.
Video footage shows that the appallingly thin dogs in the laboratory were caged::: sometimes alone::: in barren metal cells and struggled to swallow thin gruelâ€”the only food that they could eat::: given how easily they could choke. Long ropes of saliva hung from the mouths of those whose jaw muscles had weakened. Even balancing was difficult. Dogs with this condition are also at great risk of contracting pneumonia because they can easily inhale liquid. To gauge just how much a dogâ€™s muscles have deteriorated::: experimenters invented a crude technique that could pass for medieval torture: They repeatedly stretch them with a motorized lever in order to cause muscle tears.
Dogs who didnâ€™t have the disease but carried the MD gene were used for breeding. Deprived of loving homes::: they frantically paced across the slatted floors and bit the bars of the small cages in frustration. They didnâ€™t even have the comfort of a blanket.
Forty years of experiments on dogs have failed to produce a cure or even a treatment to reverse MD symptoms in humans.

At Texas A&M University::: experimenters bred golden retrievers to develop canine muscular dystrophy (MD). This disease ravages their bodies::: causing progressive muscle wasting and weakness.
Video footage shows that the appallingly thin dogs in the laboratory were caged::: sometimes alone::: in barren metal cells and struggled to swallow thin gruelâ€”the only food that they could eat::: given how easily they could choke. Long ropes of saliva hung from the mouths of those whose jaw muscles had weakened. Even balancing was difficult. Dogs with this condition are also at great risk of contracting pneumonia because they can easily inhale liquid. To gauge just how much a dogâ€™s muscles have deteriorated::: experimenters invented a crude technique that could pass for medieval torture: They repeatedly stretch them with a motorized lever in order to cause muscle tears.
Dogs who didnâ€™t have the disease but carried the MD gene were used for breeding. Deprived of loving homes::: they frantically paced across the slatted floors and bit the bars of the small cages in frustration. They didnâ€™t even have the comfort of a blanket.
Forty years of experiments on dogs have failed to produce a cure or even a treatment to reverse MD symptoms in humans.

column85:
At Texas A&M University::: experimenters bred golden retrievers to develop canine muscular dystrophy (MD). This disease ravages their bodies::: causing progressive muscle wasting and weakness.

Video footage shows that the appallingly thin dogs in the laboratory were caged::: sometimes alone::: in barren metal cells and struggled to swallow thin gruelâ€”the only food that they could eat::: given how easily they could choke. Long ropes of saliva hung from the mouths of those whose jaw muscles had weakened. Even balancing was difficult. Dogs with this condition are also at great risk of contracting pneumonia because they can easily inhale liquid. To gauge just how much a dogâ€™s muscles have deteriorated::: experimenters invented a crude technique that could pass for medieval torture: They repeatedly stretch them with a motorized lever in order to cause muscle tears.

Dogs who didnâ€™t have the disease but carried the MD gene were used for breeding. Deprived of loving homes::: they frantically paced across the slatted floors and bit the bars of the small cages in frustration. They didnâ€™t even have the comfort of a blanket.

Forty years of experiments on dogs have failed to produce a cure or even a treatment to reverse MD symptoms in humans.

At Texas A&M University::: experimenters bred golden retrievers to develop canine muscular dystrophy (MD). This disease ravages their bodies::: causing progressive muscle wasting and weakness.

TL;DR: Bigotry at Texas A&M CVMBS is being handled poorly and swept under the rug. This lackluster response from administration has created a hostile environment for LGBTQIA+ students::: faculty::: and staff. We demand that Vince Hardy be terminated::: and for policy changes to be enacted to make it clear that bigotry and hate is not welcome at A&M CVMBS.

Two days ago::: on 6/15::: Program Coordinator Vince Hardy of the Texas A&M University College of Veterinary Medicine and Biomedical Sciences wrote an email reply to an invitation to a Pride Month celebration and fundraiser for the Trevor Project. In this email::: he expressed strong and direct anti-LGBTQIA+ sentiments::: calling our community â€œsexual deviants:::â€ and said he would not â€œpromote nor celebrate sexual perversions.â€ He went on to lump queer individuals with â€œthe killing of poor innocent children:::â€ and stated that it leads to â€œGodâ€™s judgement upon a nation and its demise.â€ He then sent this email as a reply-all to an entire email list-serve in the CVMBS::: sending this message of bigotry and hatred to every single member of the faculty and staff::: residents::: interns::: and student workers working at the hospital. It was then spread to the students as well::: until this hateful message had reached the entire CVMBS.

This hateful email has created a hostile environment within my school. Knowing that a member of the staff has harbored these exclusive feelings in secret and felt comfortable enough in this college to voice those feelings to a student infuriates me â€” even if the message was only sent in reply to one student::: that air of hostility still exists in this vet school.

What is even more infuriating is the lack of appropriate response from Texas A&M CVMBS. This is a college that prides itself in its diversity::: that holds class sessions to explain the importance of Diversity::: Equity::: & Inclusion in the field of veterinary medicine. A college that proudly advertises its Aggie Allies training for LGBTQIA+ support. A college that has won MULTIPLE diversity awards::: and that holds monthly committee meetings to discuss ways to improve diversity and inclusion within the CVMBS. This is a college that I proudly attend::: and for two years now have celebrated our accomplishments
and those steps towards inclusion. This is a college that I felt entirely comfortable expressing myself as a queer student::: joining Pride SVMC and VOICE to help in the journey towards diversity.

This is a college that I am now profoundly disappointed in. In refusing to take meaningful action against blatant homophobia the CVMBS::: whether they intended to or not::: have shown that this kind of language is acceptable in our school. A weak apology from the perpetrator (first image) and a vague email from the dean mentioning â€œadministrative
stepsâ€ (second image) is not enough. Words arenâ€™t enough::: especially not vague words that do little to take responsibility for the hostile environment that has now been unearthed. Promising actions and change is not enough without action.

I wish I could say I was surprised by this lack of meaningful action. Unfortunately::: while disappointed::: I was not shocked to hear that Vince Hardy would not be fired.

Another incident of hate occurred early February of this year; on a Google Form sent out to the student body::: faculty::: staff::: and graduate students of the CVMBS::: we received a response full of racist and homophobic slurs. This event was immediately reported to the administration and were promised that they would investigate; the investigation was unsuccessful and the culprit was never found. Once that was explained to us::: the incident was never mentioned again. No public comment was distributed to the CVMBS. There was no statement that this sort of action would not be tolerated at this school. The bigot faced no consequences and the event was swept under the rug. Even today I mention that event to classmates::: faculty::: and staff who then respond with surprise::: shock::: and disgust; people who interact with us every day donâ€™t know that we were targeted in a hate crime::: because no public statement was made about the event.

So again::: I was not surprised to hear that Vince Hardy would not be facing meaningful consequences. I was not surprised to hear that Texas A&M CVMBS had its hands tied when it came to meaningful action to support LGBTQIA+ students::: faculty::: and staff. And I am profoundly disappointed in my school today.

Respectfully:::

White Coats | Class of 2023

General Miley ::: we were in the Caravan in now we got hit with a roadside bomb and they had planted that bomb almost in the center of the road so when we went right over I don't remember what happened exactly but I don't know if I think I was in the front of the explosion probably in the back seat but when they found me it was like my clothes was all ripped and I must have been in the backseat kind of hunched over and I'm thinking that the trajectory of the blast was blocked by the rear end of the Hummer but some of the other guy say they took casualties in severe wounded personnel::: and I was out man I don't know what happened after that we were they had come looking for us me when they pulled me out of the vehicle I mean I was probably unconscious and I didn't come to for 10 hours and then I woke up and then I have still didn't know where I was but GEN. MILEY was out there and he was looking for me ::: it was a horrible experience for me .

You know I was serving in the US Army and I want 18 combat tours in you know all the way Operation Neptune Spear and it was a tremendous experience you know and it's just true what they say::: War is hell.

The reason General Miley was looking for me was because we were going to go home like in 2 days and we were going to ride together back up to the states actually before I got hit and then he stayed a couple of days longer and I asked him to go ahead and go ahead and he came by the house to check up on me and you know I met him out there in the field man this guy is a top-notch guy you know he took all the lumps he went through everything he did everything they expected his own men to do and that's what makes a great officer as when you live it and you walk it ::: you talk it and you get it done.

Don't take any kind of candy coated nonsense and pay attention it might save your life.

GEN. WAU'SAU TATANKA TOWN USSF

GENERAL JUDGE ADVOCATE of the UNITED STATES of AMERICA

For many generations of Aggies::: Final Review has been seen as a rite of passage. The tradition serves as an opportunity for senior members of the Texas A&M Corps of Cadets to pass their positions on to underclassmen cadets who they had mentored::: coached::: and trained during their time on the Quad.

Due to COVID-19::: the Class of 2020 was not able to experience this tradition last spring. This year they were invited back to Aggieland and were given the experience â€“ and closure â€“ many thought they would never get.

On this Arbor Day::: meet Texas A&M's Moon Tree.

50 years ago::: Apollo 14 astronauts took seeds to the moon in a scientific experiment. Today::: a descendant of a seed is alive and growing on the event lawn in The Gardens at Texas A&M University!

Col. Mike Fossum::: Aggie astronaut and COO of Texas A&M University Galveston Campus::: talks about the inspiring significance and wonder the tree represents on our campus: tx.ag/TAMUMoonTree

The tree was brought to Aggieland by Texas A&M AgriLife::: Texas A&M Forest Service::: and the Moon Tree Foundation.

Tomorrow::: Reveille IX will retire and our Reveille-in-Training will become Reveille X::: representing Aggies::: Texas A&M::: and the love we have for Aggieland!

Thank you::: Reveille IX::: and we can't wait to meet you::: Reveille X!

column3: We visited this Aggie Muster display this past weekend. My wife and I were both very moved by it::: particularly for the young Aggies who have been called home as their life journeys began. Ned::: a German shorthaired pointer::: was born in a laboratory nine years ago. He was purposely bred to have canine muscular dystrophy. For nearly a decade experimenters at Texas A&M University tormented him in pointless studies. Ned::: who was speckled with black markings::: never had a real home. He never lived anywhere but in a kennel::: and as the disease attacked his body::: he lost what little control he had over his life. Medical records show that even as a puppy::: he suffered extensively. He gradually lost weight and became ever weaker. At just a year old::: he already struggled to stand on his hind legs. His medical records document his reduced flexibility and mobility as the years progressedâ€”and also reveal the experiments and repeated muscle biopsies that he was subjected to.

Ned was euthanized on January 8::: 2021::: finally ending nine years and seven months of unmitigated pain. While itâ€™s too late for him::: there are still 20 dogs at the universityâ€”many
of whom are healthyâ€”who also had been part of the canine MD colony and who deserve to be adopted into homes where they can know love and comfort. No amount of research money is worth such cruelty. Shut down the worthless dog laboratory!

column1:
A mandatory student testing program begins at Texas A&M on March 23::: which is meant to quickly isolate students::: slow the spread::: and increase our odds for in-person events::: graduation ceremonies::: The Big Event::: and other student activities.

The testing program only applies to students in the Bryan-College Station area::: and requires students to get tested if they live on campus::: are on-campus employees::: or are in classes only offered face-to-face.

This strategy proved very effective following a Halloween uptick last semester. St. Patrickâ€™s Day is followed almost immediately by a three-day holiday weekend for A&M faculty::: students::: and staff â€” a time when events known to have behaviors that contribute to the spread of the virus can take place. This also helps to reduce the burden on area hospitals by slowing the spread.

Students will take a test consisting of spitting into a vial::: except those who have symptoms::: feel ill::: or may have been exposed to COVID-19::: who should take a mouth swab test at the on-campus Curative kiosks or at the A.P. Beutel Health Center.

Students who can document that they tested positive for COVID-19 on or after Jan. 1::: 2021::: are not required to take the test.

Read more about the program beginning March 23: tx.ag/TestingNote21

VICE CHANCELLOR AND DEAN KATHY BANKS NAMED SOLE FINALIST TO BE TEXAS A&M PRESIDENT

TRANSCRIPT:
A&M LEGACY SOCIETY DINNER
Thursday::: April 12::: 2017 â€“ 8:30 p.m.
Hall of Champions::: Kyle Field
REMARKS:
â€¢ Twenty-five percent of our students are first generation.
â€¢ And many more face equally great obstacles to accessing a college degree::: due to finances::: family situation or geographic location.
â€¢ Access to higher education is personal with me.
â€¢ I was raised in a small town in the middle of coal-mining country in eastern Kentucky.
â€¢ I understand firsthand what happens to a community and its youth when higher education seems unattainable.
â€¢ The generous support of donors like you is critically important to helping these students realize their dreams of a better life through education.
â€¢ We often talk proudly about Texas A&M and its history as a land grant institution.
â€¢ We were established to provide access to education for the working people::: those who may have been previously excluded.
â€¢ And because of land-grant universities like Texas A&M::: first-generatio
n college students like Luis have been given access to higher education in unprecedented numbers.
â€¢ I have served in my role for six years now and it has been a remarkable adventure.
â€¢ Iâ€™ve gained an Aggie son::: an Aggie son-in-law::: an Aggie soon-to-be daughter-in-law
::: and a bit of a Texas drawl.
â€¢ I have particularly enjoyed meeting with former students and learning how Texas A&M changed your life.
â€¢ You have told me stories about arriving on campus with little knowledge of what to expect. Yet::: through the challenges faced over the years on this campus::: with the support of your fellow Aggies::: you succeeded.
â€¢ And the message that I have taken home is: â€œRemember who we areâ€
â€¢ Why is this message so important?
â€¢ Because too often in universities today::: we are caught up in the game of competition.
â€¢ We focus on rankings::: trendy programs::: recruiting the elusive â€œbestâ€ student without taking the crucial step of evaluating whether our initiatives are in sync with who we are.
â€¢ In doing so::: we risk losing that which makes us unique::: our collective Aggie spirit.
â€¢ One of the most moving events in my time as dean was a special graduation ceremony.
â€¢ In March of 2016::: we were contacted with an urgent request from Nick Brewer.
â€¢ Sadly::: Nickâ€™s father::: Jim Brewer::: a Texas A&M 1980 civil engineering graduate was ill with pancreatic cancer.
â€¢ Jimâ€™s daughter::: Jenny::: was scheduled to graduate in May with an aerospace engineering degree.
â€¢ Jim told Nick that one of his last wishes was to see Jenny graduate from Texas A&M Engineering.
â€¢ Jim was not doing well in mid-March. The doctors told the family that the end was near.
â€¢ Nick asked if we could hold a special graduation ceremony for Jenny.
â€¢ One week later::: with help from the university and the association::: Jim witnessed Jennyâ€™s graduation from Texas A&M with full regalia and ceremony at his home.
â€¢ Jim lost his battle with cancer two weeks later.
â€¢ As we were preparing for the ceremony::: there were no arguments about process::: proper approvals::: or transcripts.
â€¢ We made it happen.
â€¢ We remembered who we are.
â€¢ The past six years have been a period of significant academic change.
â€¢ But::: before any new program was implemented::: we first evaluated whether it aligned with our core values. This meant at times we did not follow the same path as other universities.
â€¢ We have forged a new path.
â€¢ For example:
o To insure there is access to an Aggie engineering degree::: we increased our entering class size and retention::: and also developed a community college transitional program.
o To insure that our students are prepared for life outside of the university::: we hired 75 professors of practice with many years of industry experience.
o And to insure our students experience the world outside of the classroom::: we require all of our students to complete a non-credit extracurricular
project.
â€¢ All of these changes are unique to Texas A&M.
â€¢ When asked by my peers about the risk of not following the path of other top universities::: I reply: Aggies are not followers::: we lead.
â€¢ We have a history of service.
â€¢ We stand up when others fall back.
â€¢ We provide an excellent education and opportunity to those who seek it.
â€¢ And we continue to face new challenges.
â€¢ Most of the jobs our students will be taking in 2030 havenâ€™t been invented yet. How do you prepare a student for a job that doesnâ€™t even exist?
â€¢ How do we focus on deep learning without stifling creativity?
â€¢ How do we select students with high potential from both urban and rural areas::: who possess preparation::: talent and grit::: yet will embrace our core values?
â€¢ How do we remain custodians of the past while serving as creators of the future?
â€¢ These solutions will be complicated and will require all of us to find the proper balance.
â€¢ But I promise you: o As we move into the future::: with all of the unknowns in our changing and dynamic world.
â€¢ As we face the challenges of educating a new generation of students with different life experiences and learning styles:::
â€¢ And as we consider how to best serve our state and the nation.
â€¢ We will always remember who we are. We are Texas A&M.

Here is a link to Dr. Banksâ€™ thoughts regarding our Alma Mater...
Last bullet point speaks volumes.

VICE CHANCELLOR AND DEAN KATHY BANKS NAMED SOLE FINALIST TO BE TEXAS A&M PRESIDENT

TRANSCRIPT:
A&M LEGACY SOCIETY DINNER
Thursday::: April 12::: 2017 â€“ 8:30 p.m.
Hall of Champions::: Kyle Field
REMARKS:
â€¢ Twenty-five percent of our students are first generation.
â€¢ And many more face equally great obstacles to accessing a college degree::: due to finances::: family situation or geographic location.
â€¢ Access to higher education is personal with me.
â€¢ I was raised in a small town in the middle of coal-mining country in eastern Kentucky.
â€¢ I understand firsthand what happens to a community and its youth when higher education seems unattainable.
â€¢ The generous support of donors like you is critically important to helping these students realize their dreams of a better life through education.
â€¢ We often talk proudly about Texas A&M and its history as a land grant institution.
â€¢ We were established to provide access to education for the working people::: those who may have been previously excluded.
â€¢ And because of land-grant universities like Texas A&M::: first-generatio
n college students like Luis have been given access to higher education in unprecedented numbers.
â€¢ I have served in my role for six years now and it has been a remarkable adventure.
â€¢ Iâ€™ve gained an Aggie son::: an Aggie son-in-law::: an Aggie soon-to-be daughter-in-law
::: and a bit of a Texas drawl.
â€¢ I have particularly enjoyed meeting with former students and learning how Texas A&M changed your life.
â€¢ You have told me stories about arriving on campus with little knowledge of what to expect. Yet::: through the challenges faced over the years on this campus::: with the support of your fellow Aggies::: you succeeded.
â€¢ And the message that I have taken home is: â€œRemember who we areâ€
â€¢ Why is this message so important?
â€¢ Because too often in universities today::: we are caught up in the game of competition.
â€¢ We focus on rankings::: trendy programs::: recruiting the elusive â€œbestâ€ student without taking the crucial step of evaluating whether our initiatives are in sync with who we are.
â€¢ In doing so::: we risk losing that which makes us unique::: our collective Aggie spirit.
â€¢ One of the most moving events in my time as dean was a special graduation ceremony.
â€¢ In March of 2016::: we were contacted with an urgent request from Nick Brewer.
â€¢ Sadly::: Nickâ€™s father::: Jim Brewer::: a Texas A&M 1980 civil engineering graduate was ill with pancreatic cancer.
â€¢ Jimâ€™s daughter::: Jenny::: was scheduled to graduate in May with an aerospace engineering degree.
â€¢ Jim told Nick that one of his last wishes was to see Jenny graduate from Texas A&M Engineering.
â€¢ Jim was not doing well in mid-March. The doctors told the family that the end was near.
â€¢ Nick asked if we could hold a special graduation ceremony for Jenny.
â€¢ One week later::: with help from the university and the association::: Jim witnessed Jennyâ€™s graduation from Texas A&M with full regalia and ceremony at his home.
â€¢ Jim lost his battle with cancer two weeks later.
â€¢ As we were preparing for the ceremony::: there were no arguments about process::: proper approvals::: or transcripts.
â€¢ We made it happen.
â€¢ We remembered who we are.
â€¢ The past six years have been a period of significant academic change.
â€¢ But::: before any new program was implemented::: we first evaluated whether it aligned with our core values. This meant at times we did not follow the same path as other universities.
â€¢ We have forged a new path.
â€¢ For example:
o To insure there is access to an Aggie engineering degree::: we increased our entering class size and retention::: and also developed a community college transitional program.
o To insure that our students are prepared for life outside of the university::: we hired 75 professors of practice with many years of industry experience.
o And to insure our students experience the world outside of the classroom::: we require all of our students to complete a non-credit extracurricular
project.
â€¢ All of these changes are unique to Texas A&M.
â€¢ When asked by my peers about the risk of not following the path of other top universities::: I reply: Aggies are not followers::: we lead.
â€¢ We have a history of service.
â€¢ We stand up when others fall back.
â€¢ We provide an excellent education and opportunity to those who seek it.
â€¢ And we continue to face new challenges.
â€¢ Most of the jobs our students will be taking in 2030 havenâ€™t been invented yet. How do you prepare a student for a job that doesnâ€™t even exist?
â€¢ How do we focus on deep learning without stifling creativity?
â€¢ How do we select students with high potential from both urban and rural areas::: who possess preparation::: talent and grit::: yet will embrace our core values?
â€¢ How do we remain custodians of the past while serving as creators of the future?
â€¢ These solutions will be complicated and will require all of us to find the proper balance.
â€¢ But I promise you: o As we move into the future::: with all of the unknowns in our changing and dynamic world.
â€¢ As we face the challenges of educating a new generation of students with different life experiences and learning styles:::
â€¢ And as we consider how to best serve our state and the nation.
â€¢ We will always remember who we are. We are Texas A&M.

column14: I read the article::: and while it has good suggestions::: it is incomplete and misleading. More connections with surrounding states would not have persuaded surrounding states to send us electricity they desperately needed themselves. While winterizing the wind turbines would have helped and will help in the future::: wind is not a dependable source of electricity. Much more important is to ensure that every plant::: renewable or otherwise::: committed to providing electricity is capable of providing electricity under a more expanded range of temperatures. Forcing them to upgrade will be the key limiting step. We need political will to either proportionally penalize the plants for failure in the future or fund the upgrades with state money. ERCOT needs to take a more active role in ensuring readiness::: and it may take new powers from new state laws. One thing that will not help is personal attacks::: on politicians or ERCOT boardmembers.

column69: Posted from a friend regarding ERCOT and how it all happened. We can thank the Biden administration. Unbelievable.  An Emergency Order from the Biden administrationâ€™ s Department of Energy shows Texas energy grid operator ERCOT was instructed to stay within green energy standards by purchasing energy from outside the state at a higher cost::: throttling power output throughout the state ahead of a catastrophic polar vortex.  Going into effect Sunday::: Feb. 14::: Emergency Order 202-21-1 shows the Energy Dept. was aware of Texas Gov. Greg Abbottâ€™s statewide disaster declaration and that ERCOT was readying gas utilities in preparation for a demand surge.  The order shows Acting Energy Secretary David Huizenga did not waive environmental restrictions to allow for maximum energy output::: instead ordering ERCOT to utilize all resources in order to stay within acceptable emissions standards â€“ including purchasing energy from outside the state.  â€œERCOT anticipates that this Order may result in exceedance of emissions of sulfur dioxide::: nitrogen oxide::: mercury::: and carbon monoxide emissions::: as well as wastewater release limits:::â€ the order states. â€œTo minimize adverse environmental impacts::: this Order limits operation of dispatched units to the times and within the parameters determined by ERCOT for reliability purposes.â€  Moreover::: the order instructed an â€œincremental amount of restricted capacityâ€ to be sold to ERCOT at â€œa price no lower than $1:::500/MWh:::â€ an increase of over 6:::000 percent over February 2020 prices of $18.20.  On Wednesday::: the Dallas Business Journal reported::: â€œElectricity on the Texas grid has averaged about $1:::137.33 per megawatt hour so far in February::: up from $18.20 per megawatt hour in February 2020::: according to data from the Electricity Reliability Council of Texas. Thatâ€™s a jump of more than 6:::000 percent.â€  Days later::: the Public Utility Commission of Texas set prices at $9:::000/MWh.  The EO shows the Biden administration basically ordered ERCOT to throttle its energy output by forcing it to comply with environmental green energy standards::: while knowing full well Texans could freeze to death in their homes with zero electricity as temperatures plunged into the single digits.
column70: HERE IS THE OPINION ARTICLE - For those who say they canâ€™t get it w/o a subscriptionâ€”â€”-  Millions of Texans have experienced power outages at a time when electricity seems to be most needed::: during the worst winter storm in decades.The Electric Reliability Council of Texas and utility engineers around the state are working around the clock to fix the problem::: but it still remains to be seen when power will be restored to all customers. Texas::: the energy capital of the country::: does not seem to be able to supply the power needed in severe weather.  Here we would like to present our perspectives in simple non-technical terms on what happened::: why did it happen and what could be done to prevent it from happening again. Our goal is to stimulate conversations among citizens::: utilities::: system operators::: regulatory bodies and academia so that this experience will serve as a wake-up call to address the criticality of our energy infrastructure as we make progress toward a more resilient and sustainable future.  What happened?  Unprecedented winter storms and frigid temperatures hit across the state beginning on Sunday::: causing more than 30 gigawatts of generation capacity to be taken off-line. On the demand side::: due to this cold weather::: the electric load hit a record of more than 69GW on that night. In response to this combination of historically high demand and unprecedented shortage of power supply::: ERCOT initiated â€œEnergy Emergency Alert 3â€ which ordered transmission companies to begin rotating outages across the state. Meanwhile::: skyrocketing demand for natural gas to heat homes in the frigid conditions meant the already stretched supply of gas available for electricity generation was even further compromised. Why did this happen in Texas::: often touted as the energy capital of the country (if not the world)? While final answers await a comprehensive investigation::: several key factors may have contributed to this historic power outage.  First::: unlike the interconnected regional grids that serve most of the rest of the country::: Texasâ€™s ERCOT grid essentially stands on its own. This limits power import and export during extreme situations. When states like Minnesota or California have extreme weather conditions::: they can draw upon inter-state power transmission lines to get power from the interconnection . The Texas grid is largely an isolated grid from the eastern and western interconnection s that serve the rest of the country.  Second::: the massive natural gas and wind generation infrastructure in Texas is not ready for such a winter storm. Many turbines were shut down due to the freezing weather. Equipping these wind turbines with anti-freezing technologies is doable::: but will require additional investments. Third::: so called â€œdemand response:::â€ the synchronization mechanism of demand and supply::: which is a smart grid technology to extract flexibility at the customer end::: is still in a nascent stage here. Other than urging customers to practice voluntary energy conservation::: currently there are very few organized technology and business mechanisms to enable load-serving entities to reduce demand at peak periods to manageable levels. This could be automatically done at the customer end by prioritizing essential services such as lighting over non-essential services such as laundry.  How it can be fixed  While our state is still in the midst of this immediate crisis::: we would like to offer a few strategic::: actionable items for the state and for Texans. Resiliency will need to be on top of every decision makerâ€™s mind. In particular::: to better prepare the Texas grid for future extreme events::: we recommend the following actions. * We need to winterize wind turbines and other generating infrastructure for extreme conditions.  * We should invest in additional High Voltage DC lines to connect ERCOT with both Eastern and Western interconnection s::: so that we can draw upon imports/ exports when the supply of electricity becomes more volatile.  * We need the regulatory and market design to scale up implementation of demand response. The necessary technologies::: including smart meters on most of our houses::: are already there. What is missing is the proper market mechanics::: such as proper crediting of demand contribution::: and the political will to promote wide adoption.  * Last but not least::: just as we have developed strategic oil reserves::: it is high time to think about strategic energy storage reserves. Electric energy storage would go a long way during this time to minimize hardship for millions of Texans. Much research and innovation will be needed to fully develop the potential of energy storage at grid scale.  While it is cold comfort in the middle of a crisis::: what we are experiencing now are the growing pains of the transition to new technologies and new energy resources. However::: with actions such as those above::: we will be better prepared for whatever Nature may throw at us in the future.

column1: Over the past week::: Aggies have quietly demonstrated acts of selfless service in response to the winter weather.  Last night::: more than 300 members of the Texas A&M Corps of Cadets volunteered to help identify burst pipes across campus. They thoroughly canvassed 200 buildings on campus::: finding many leaks. Their efforts helped stabilize water issues at a time when many SSC at TAMU employees could not drive to campus.  Cadets have also been aiding the local chapter of the American Red Cross Serving Central and South Texas and the Brazos Valley Food Bank at the Reed Arena warming center & in the community.  Additionally::: Staci Rende '19 has helped coordinate "Aggieland Relief:::" a drive asking the public to donate blankets::: jackets::: coats::: socks::: gloves::: bottled water::: non-perishable food::: camping gear::: clothes::: and towels. The drive will be set up from 10 a.m. to 3 p.m. Friday in the Reed Arena parking lot next to West Campus Garage.  Read more about these acts of selfless service and how you can donate to Aggieland Relief here: tx.ag/AggieResponse

column88: Judy Brewer::: please share this with Jay. Echoing what Eric Brown said::: Col. Jay O. Brewer has been a part of the Aggie Band and Texas A&M for 44 of the bandâ€™s 126 years. Putting that into perspective:  - every band class from the Class of â€˜78 to the Class of â€˜24 has known a fish Brewer::: Mr. Brewer::: Sir!::: Jay::: 2LT/1LT/CAPT/ MAJ/LTC/COL Brewer  - when Col. Brewer entered as fish Brewer it was the beginning of Joe T. Haneyâ€™s fifth year as Aggie Band director. When Jay Brewer graduated in 1981::: Joe Haney asked him to stay on and help run the Aggie Band  - Haney had briefly attended A&M and marched in the Aggie Band under Col. E. V. Adams before being drafted into the Army. He later studied music at SMU and built the Mexia High School band program before being personally selected by Col. Adams as his replacement in 1973. Col. Haney wrote the Aggie Bandâ€™s signature March::: â€œNoble Men of Kyleâ€. Col. Haney also taught private lessons to a young Ray Toler during summer visits back home in Marlin::: TX. Toler grew up to be an Air Force band director and was Col. Haneyâ€™s personal choice to replace him in 1989.  - LTC E. V. Adams â€˜29 was the longest-serving director of the Aggie Band from 1946-1973. It was LTC Adams that created many of the signature drill designs that the Aggie Band is known for today. While a student::: Adams was told by his director::: Col. Richard. J. Dunn::: that he should keep studying music because Dunn wanted Adams to come back some day and take over as Aggie Band director. While growing up in College Station::: Adams was also taught how to play the trumpet by Alois Slovacek::: another former Aggie bandmaster  - Col. Richard J. Dunn was Aggie Band director from 1924-1946. He introduced many traditions including the Block T::: the bugle rank::: and wrote the music for â€œThe Spirit of Aggieland. Col. Dunn was a veteran of the Spanish American War::: studied at the Grand Conservatory in NYC::: and was offered a position in John Philip Sousaâ€™s Marine Band but declined it for his desire to be an Army bandmaster::: a goal he achieved in 1911 when he became Bandmaster of the U. S. 11th Infantry Band. It was under Col. Dunn that the Aggie Band first became â€œnationally famousâ€  In summary::: Col. Jay Brewer has served the Aggie Band longer than any other staff member ever. His career spans the terms of three Aggie band directors and connects in an unbroken line all the way back to Col. Richard Dunn in 1924. Upon his retirement::: it will be the first time since 1946 that a former member of the Aggie Band hasnâ€™t been on band staff. Besides being the â€œVoice of the Aggie Bandâ€ since 1981::: he has been involved in rehearsals::: directing::: administrative duties::: instrument repair::: counseling cadets::: and contributing to the history and lore of the Fightinâ€™ Texas Aggie Band. He will certainly be missed by generations of Aggies but he wonâ€™t be forgotten. Even today::: there are current Aggie Band members who are the children of former band members who marched while Col. Brewer was on staff. Years from now::: their children will also join the Aggie Band and hear stories from their parents about Col. Brewer.  Gig â€˜em! Jason Johnston Aggie Band â€˜94

column9: Right now::: 24 dogsâ€”at least 12 of whom are perfectly healthy::: adoptable::: and without disease symptomsâ€”are still being warehoused in Texas A&M University's canine muscular dystrophy (MD) laboratory::: despite the retirement of lead experimenter Joe Kornegay and the lack of funding for new experiments.  The golden retrievers and other dogs in the laboratory are deprived of the very things that make their life worth living::: as they spend every day stuck in barren metal cells. The dogs suffering from canine MD have undergone painful and terrifying testing::: and their health has steadily deteriorated to the point where it's difficult for them even to swallow their own saliva. Video footage shows that the healthy ones pace frantically and bite at the bars of their cages in frustration.  It's commendable that Texas A&M made the compassionate decision to stop breeding dogs to develop MD in 2019. Please do the next right thing and use your authority as a regent to order the release of the surviving dogs from the MD laboratory so that they may live the remaining years of their lives in warm::: loving adoptive homes.  Thank you for your consideration of this important matter.  Sincerely

column6: Right now::: 25 dogsâ€”at least 12 of whom are perfectly healthy::: adoptable::: and without disease symptomsâ€”are still being warehoused in Texas A&M University's canine muscular dystrophy (MD) laboratory::: despite the retirement of lead experimenter Joe Kornegay and the lack of funding for new experiments.  The golden retrievers and other dogs in the laboratory are deprived of the very things that make their life worth living::: as they spend every day stuck in barren metal cells. The dogs suffering from canine MD have undergone painful and terrifying testing::: and their health has steadily deteriorated to the point where it's difficult for them even to swallow their own saliva. Video footage shows that the healthy ones pace frantically and bite at the bars of their cages in frustration.  It's commendable that Texas A&M made the compassionate decision to stop breeding dogs to develop MD in 2019. Please do the next right thing and use your authority as a regent to order the release of the surviving dogs from the MD laboratory so that they may live the remaining years of their lives in warm::: loving adoptive homes.  Thank you for your consideration of this important matter.

column181: Houston Chronicle-2013. Very first Aggie identified as great-great grandfather of 2 current students By Carol Christian | October 22::: 2013 | Updated: October 22::: 2013 3:17pm Ã¡ E-mail Ã¡ Print Tweet 0 Page 1 of 1 Texas A&M University senior Lindsay Lawrence and her younger brother Zachary Lawrence are fifth-generatio n Aggies::: an undoubtedly small group. But the pair from Shiner can also claim an even more elite status - direct descendants of the man believed to be the school's very first enrollee. John Archibald McIver::: from Caldwell about 25 miles west of College Station::: was apparently the first student to enroll in A&M's first session::: which started on Oct. 4::: 1876. He was incorrectly listed as James Archibald McIver in the first student directory but a correction was made in the next year's list::: according to a university news release. Since A&M was the state's first public institution of higher learning::: that would make McIver the first student to enroll at a public college in Texas. Zachary Lawrence::: who is McIver's great-great-gra ndson::: is a sophomore psychology major and::: like the Aggie men in his family's four prior generations::: a member of the school's Corps of Cadets. Lindsay Lawrence::: who is not on campus this term::: is majoring in allied health. An older brother::: Ryan Lawrence ::: graduated from A&M last spring. They are related to McIver through his granddaughter::: Patsy McIver Lawrence ::: who is the wife of Allen S. Lawrence Jr. and their paternal grandmother. An often-told story in the Lawrence family history supports the belief that McIver was the first Aggie::: the news release said. "What I've often heard family members say is that he rode over on horseback from Caldwell to enroll but was told he was a day early:::" Zachary Lawrence said in a statement. "Rather than ride back to Caldwell as he had planned::: he decided just to stay overnight. He slept under a tree that night and then registered the next morning." The family has copies of newspaper stories reporting McIver's death in 1923 and noting he was the first student to register at Texas A&M. Also::: a photo of McIver is on display in the Sanders Corps of Cadets Hall of Honor on campus and includes a caption describing him as "the first student to register at the Agricultural and Mechanical College of Texas :::" as the school was known until 1963. School officials learned about the Lawrences' connection to Aggie history not from the students themselves but through a tweet from a former classmate of their father to Texas A&M President R. Bowen Loftin ::: the release stated. Asked why he had not mentioned this connection::: Zachary said he didn't want his family connection to be a factor in his admission::: according to the release. "I wanted to get into Texas A&M on my own merits:::" he said. column5: Right now::: 25 dogsâ€”at least 12 of whom are perfectly healthy::: adoptable::: and without disease symptomsâ€”are still being warehoused in Texas A&M University's canine muscular dystrophy (MD) laboratory::: despite the retirement of lead experimenter Joe Kornegay and the lack of funding for new experiments.  The golden retrievers and other dogs in the laboratory are deprived of the very things that make their life worth living::: as they spend every day stuck in barren metal cells. The dogs suffering from canine MD have undergone painful and terrifying testing::: and their health has steadily deteriorated to the point where it's difficult for them even to swallow their own saliva. Video footage shows that the healthy ones pace frantically and bite at the bars of their cages in frustration.  It's commendable that Texas A&M made the compassionate decision to stop breeding dogs to develop MD in 2019. Please do the next right thing and use your authority as a regent to order the release of the surviving dogs from the MD laboratory so that they may live the remaining years of their lives in warm::: loving adoptive homes.  Thank you for your consideration of this important matter.

column18: Right now::: 25 dogsâ€”at least 12 of whom are perfectly healthy::: adoptable::: and without disease symptomsâ€”are still being warehoused in Texas A&M University's canine muscular dystrophy (MD) laboratory::: despite the retirement of lead experimenter Joe Kornegay and the lack of funding for new experiments.  The golden retrievers and other dogs in the laboratory are deprived of the very things that make their life worth living::: as they spend every day stuck in barren metal cells. The dogs suffering from canine MD have undergone painful and terrifying testing::: and their health has steadily deteriorated to the point where it's difficult for them even to swallow their own saliva. Video footage shows that the healthy ones pace frantically and bite at the bars of their cages in frustration.  It's commendable that Texas A&M made the compassionate decision to stop breeding dogs to develop MD in 2019. Please do the next right thing and use your authority as a regent to order the release of the surviving dogs from the MD laboratory so that they may live the remaining years of their lives in warm::: loving adoptive homes.  Thank you for your consideration of this important matter.

column45: Herpes is a sexually transmitted virus that primarily infects the mouth and the genitals. It is transmitted by bodily fluids â€“ penetration isnâ€™t required for transmission::: oral-oral or oral-genital contact will suffice:::There are two types of herpes simplex virus: HSV-1 and HSV-2. Both virus types can cause sores around the mouth (herpes labialis) and on the genitals (genital herpes). Cold sores are caused by the herpes simplex virus (HSV). Cold sores sometimes called fever blisters::: are groups of small blisters on the lip and around the mouth. The skin around the blisters is often red::: swollen::: and sore. The blisters may break open::: leak a clear fluid::: and then scab over after a few days. They usually heal in several days to 2 weeks. The herpes simplex virus usually enters the body through a break in the skin around or inside the mouth. It is usually spread when a person touches a cold sore or touches infected fluidâ€”such as from sharing eating utensils or razors::: kissing an infected person::: or touching that person's saliva. A parent who has a cold sore often spreads the infection to his or her child in this way. Cold sores can also be spread to other areas of the body. Luckly there is a cure for herpes Contact Dr Odia Via:(Dr Odia Herbalist home on Facebook)

column18: NEW YORK TIMES: UP TO 90% OF PEOPLE WITH â€œPOSITIVEâ€ COVID TEST RESULTS ARENâ€™T INFECTIOUS by Kevin Ryan  â€œYour Coronavirus Test Is Positive. Maybe It Shouldnâ€™t Be.â€  Thatâ€™s the title of a New York Times article today that has very significant implications for COVID policy moving forward.  â€œThe standard tests are diagnosing huge numbers of people who may be carrying relatively insignificant amounts of the virus. Most of these people are not likely to be contagious:::â€ the New York Times writes.  â€œThe tests being used are too sensitive::: meaning they pick up even tiny fragments of virus that do not indicate a person is actually meaningfully infected.â€  Indeed an investigation by the newspaper finds that up to 90% of positive test results are in people who are not infectious.  THE EXPLANATION  The PCR test searches for the virus by amplifying virus materials::: essentially growing them in amplification â€œcyclesâ€ until they are detectable. The smaller the amount of virus::: the more cycles are needed to detect it.  Often the test uses so many amplification cycles that even the tiniest genetic fragments â€“ leftovers from infection that pose no risk whatsoever â€“ trigger positive test results.  And the test result merely returns â€œPositiveâ€ or â€œNegativeâ€::: with no indication of how much virus was found::: or how many amplification cycles were needed to find the virus (called the cycle threshold).  THE PROBLEM  A test result that simply says positive or negative â€œisnâ€™t good enoughâ€ according the doctors interviewed for the New York Times article. Itâ€™s the AMOUNT of virus found that should dictate whether the test result should be categorized as positive::: and what the patient should do next.  â€œItâ€™s really irresponsible:::â€ Dr. Michael Mina::: an epidemiologist at the Harvard T.H. Chan School of Public Health. â€œWeâ€™ve been using one type of data for everything::: and that is just plus or minus â€” thatâ€™s all. Weâ€™re using that for clinical diagnostics::: for public health::: for policy decision-making .â€  â€œItâ€™s just kind of mind-blowing to meâ€¦ that theyâ€™re just returning a positive or a negative:::â€ said Angela Rasmussen::: a virologist at Columbia University in New York. â€œIt would be useful information to know if somebodyâ€™s positive::: whether they have a high viral load or a low viral load:::â€ she added.  Just how many of the â€œpositiveâ€ test results are from patients who have so little virus that they arenâ€™t infectious?  The New York Times reviewed three sets of testing data from Massachusetts::: New York::: and Nevada. It found that 90% of people who tested â€œpositiveâ€ carried barely any virus.  If that rate holds true for the entire county::: it would mean that the United States has far fewer actual infectious cases of COVID than is being reported.  â€œOn Thursday::: the United States recorded 45:::604 new coronavirus cases::: according to a database maintained by The Times. If the rates of contagiousness in Massachusetts and New York were to apply nationwide::: then perhaps only 4:::500 of those people may actually need to isolate and submit to contact tracing:::â€ the Times wrote.  Experts informed of these numbers were stunned.  â€œIâ€™m shocked that people would think that [such small amounts of virus] could represent a positive:::â€ Juliet Morrison::: a virologist at the University of California::: Riverside::: said.  â€œI would say that none of those people should be contact-traced::: not one:::â€ Dr. Mina said.  The number of people with positive results who arenâ€™t infectious is particularly concerning::: said Scott Becker::: executive director of the Association of Public Health Laboratories. â€œThat worries me a lot.â€  â€œIâ€™m really shockedâ€ Dr. Ashish Jha::: director of the Harvard Global Health Institute::: agreed. â€œBoy::: does it really change the way we need to be thinking about testing.â€  THE IMPLICATIONS  Just yesterday::: California revamped its criteria for reopening businesses::: basing it on how many positive test results a county has instead of hospitalization s::: and setting the bar incredibly low. Just 1 new positive test per day out of 15:::000 residents now keeps a county at the strictest level where nearly all businesses are shut down or heavily restricted.  But todayâ€™s revelation by the New York Times shows that such a move will essentially keep the state permanently locked down with little regard for how many of those positive test results are actually from infectious Californians::: and how many are from overly sensitive PCR tests.  Indeed::: most of the case-based measurements that the media has been using to gauge how the states are doing at controlling COVID may now be all but meaningless in light of the New York Times data.  Also::: comparing the summer â€œsurgeâ€ in some states to the spring outbreak is also now less meaningful. In the spring::: only symptomatic people were being tested. Symptomatic people are those who have the highest viral loads::: and therefore did not need a lot of â€œamplificationâ€ in their tests to result in a positive test.  But in the summer::: the guidelines switched to testing more people::: including those who were not symptomatic. This likely resulted in significantly more â€œpositiveâ€ results from non-infectious patients.  THE SOLUTION  One solution would be to adjust the cycle threshold used to decide if a patient is infected. Most tests set the limit at 40. â€œAny test with a cycle threshold above 35 is too sensitiveâ€ scientists interviewed by the Times agreed. Dr. Mina said he would set the figure at 30::: or even less.  From 70% to 90% of tests would no longer be judged positive if the amplification cycles were limited to 30::: according to the Times.  And less sensitive::: rapid tests should be used to verify positive PCR results::: Dr. Mina said.  â€œIn what may be a step in this direction::: the Trump administration announced on Thursday that it would purchase 150 million rapid tests:::â€ the New York Times article said.  SOURCES: https:// www.nytimes.com/ 2020/08/29/ health/ coronavirus-test ing.html https:// covid19.ca.gov/ safer-economy/
